#let images = (
  "21.1": (
    caption: [Angiosperm life cycle showing alternation of generations between diploid sporophyte and haploid gametophyte. The diagram illustrates microsporogenesis in the anther producing microspores that develop into microgametophytes (pollen grains), and megasporogenesis in the ovule producing megaspores that develop into the megagametophyte (embryo sac). Double fertilization occurs when two sperm cells fertilize both the egg cell and the central cell, forming the zygote and primary endosperm cell respectively.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.2": (
    caption: [Anther structure and development in Arabidopsis. Cross section showing four microsporangia of a mature anther containing pollen mother cells. The developmental sequence shows differentiation of cell layers (L1, L2, L3) into epidermis, endothecium, middle layer, and tapetum. Sporogeneous cells differentiate into pollen mother cells (microsporocytes) that undergo meiosis to produce microspores.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.3": (
    caption: [Male gametophyte development through microsporogenesis and microgametogenesis. Microsporogenesis begins with meiosis of pollen mother cells producing tetrads of microspores. Microgametogenesis involves asymmetric mitosis producing vegetative cell and generative cell at the bicellular stage. Development diverges into either bicellular pollen (shed before second mitosis) or tricellular pollen (generative cell divides to form two sperm cells before pollen release).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.4": (
    caption: [Pollen grain cell wall structure showing multilayered architecture. Scanning electron microscopy reveals diverse sculptural ornamentation on pollen surfaces from different species. Cross-sectional diagram shows the complex wall layers: outer exine (composed of sexine with tectum and columella, plus nexine I and II) containing sporopollenin, and inner intine composed of cellulose and pectins. Lacunae and sculptural elements create species-specific patterns important for pollination.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.5": (
    caption: [Arabidopsis pollen grain apertures and tube emergence. Scanning electron microscopy shows three elongated furrow apertures where the exine wall is weakened and thinner. The INAPERTURATE POLLEN1 gene controls aperture number and size: mutation eliminates apertures while overexpression produces supernumerary apertures. Pollen tubes can emerge through apertures or occasionally rupture the exine outside apertures.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.6": (
    caption: [Structure of the Arabidopsis gynoecium (pistil) showing fused carpel organization. The gynoecium consists of two fused carpels (valves) separated by a medial septum. Cross-sectional view reveals replum tissue joining valves and septum, placental tissue bearing ovules, and the transmitting tract through which pollen tubes grow. Each valve represents a separate carpel.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.7": (
    caption: [Ovule morphogenesis in Arabidopsis showing developmental stages and tissue differentiation. Three distinct zones form from meristematic layers: L1 (pink) produces epidermis, L2 (yellow) gives rise to integuments and chalaza, and L3 (blue) forms the funiculus. The nucellus develops at the micropylar end containing the megaspore mother cell. Two integument layers grow to surround the nucellus, leaving the micropyle opening. The mature embryo sac contains the central cell with diploid nucleus formed by polar nuclei fusion.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.8": (
    caption: [Developmental stages in the Polygonum-type embryo sac of Arabidopsis. The megaspore mother cell undergoes meiosis producing four megaspores, three of which degenerate. The functional megaspore undergoes three rounds of free nuclear mitotic divisions creating an eight-nucleate syncytium. Cellularization produces seven cells: three antipodal cells at the chalazal pole (often degenerate before fertilization), egg apparatus at the micropylar pole (egg cell flanked by two synergids), and the large central cell with diploid nucleus from polar nuclei fusion.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.9": (
    caption: [Diagram of the egg apparatus and filiform apparatus of the Polygonum-type embryo sac. The egg apparatus consists of the egg cell flanked by two synergid cells at the micropylar end. Each synergid contains a filiform apparatus - a convoluted, thickened cell wall structure that increases plasma membrane surface area. The filiform apparatus plays crucial roles in pollen tube attraction, discharge of pollen tube contents, and facilitating gamete fusion during fertilization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.10": (
    caption: [Progamic phase of reproduction in Arabidopsis showing six sequential steps of pollen tube growth and guidance. Step 1: Pollen grain adheres, hydrates, and germinates on stigma papilla cell. Step 2: Pollen tube invades stigma and grows through papillar cell wall. Step 3: Tube grows through nutrient-rich extracellular matrix of transmitting tract. Step 4: Tube exits transmitting tract near ovule. Step 5: Tube grows along septum and funiculus toward micropyle. Step 6: Tube penetrates micropyle, enters synergid cell, and bursts to release two sperm cells. Graph shows pollen tube growth rates across angiosperms range from 10 μm/h to over 20,000 μm/h, averaging 100 times faster than gymnosperms.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.11": (
    caption: [Adhesion and hydration of pollen grains on Arabidopsis stigmas. Scanning electron microscopy shows stigmatic papilla cells with characteristic surface features. Transmission electron microscopy reveals the "foot" structure - lipid-rich material connecting pollen grain to stigma cell surface. Four developmental stages: adhesion of pollen to papilla, foot formation and hydration through capillary system in lipid reorganization, pollen tube emergence from grain, and tube growth through papilla cell wall toward style.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.12": (
    caption: [Pollen tube elongating by tip growth mechanism. The cytoplasm is concentrated in the growing apical region while large vacuoles and callose partitions compartmentalize the tube. Tip growth occurs exclusively at the apex through localized exocytosis of cell wall precursors. This extreme polarization enables rapid growth rates up to 6 μm per second in some species, making pollen tubes among the fastest growing cells in nature, capable of reaching lengths up to 40 cm.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.13": (
    caption: [Clear zone of a growing pollen tube showing specialized apical organization. Light microscopy and electron microscopy reveal the "clear zone" at the extreme tip - an inverted cone-shaped region containing Golgi bodies, fine F-actin filaments, and numerous small secretory vesicles but lacking large organelles. The clear zone represents the site of active exocytosis where vesicles fuse with the plasma membrane to deliver cell wall materials. Cytoplasmic streaming circulates on either side of the central axis. Long actin filaments supporting organelle streaming begin at the basal edges of the clear zone.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.14": (
    caption: [Cytosolic concentration gradients in tobacco pollen tubes visualized with fluorescent probes. Color-coded gradients show high (red) to low (blue) concentrations of calcium ions, pH/H+ ions, chloride ions, and short actin filaments at the tube tip. The acidic tip corresponds to the secretory vesicle region. The calcium and acidic gradients define the clear zone. Long actin filaments supporting organelle streaming begin at the basal edges of these ion gradients. Extracellular H+ flux pattern correlates with absence of plasma membrane H+-ATPase NtAHA1 at the tip. Similar pH gradient patterns occur in Arabidopsis pollen tubes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.15": (
    caption: [Diagram of GEF activation of a GTPase molecular switch mechanism. GTPases cycle between an active GTP-binding form and an inactive GDP-binding form. Guanine nucleotide exchange factors (GEFs) promote exchange of GDP for GTP, activating the GTPase. GTPase-activating proteins (GAPs) stimulate GTP hydrolysis, inactivating the switch. This molecular mechanism regulates pollen tube tip growth by controlling localized cell expansion through modulation of cytoskeletal dynamics and vesicle trafficking.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.16": (
    caption: [Use of excised Torenia fournieri ovules to study pollen tube guidance in vitro. This experimental system allows direct observation and manipulation of pollen tube behavior near the female gametophyte. Ovules excised from ovary tissue can attract pollen tubes growing in culture medium. The system enabled discovery of pollen tube attractant peptides and elucidation of guidance mechanisms. Light microscopy images show pollen tubes responding to ovule signals and growing toward the micropyle entrance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.17": (
    caption: [Sperm cell behavior during double fertilization divided into three stages. Stage 1: Pollen tube enters embryo sac through a synergid cell and releases two sperm cells along with vegetative nucleus. Stage 2: Sperm cells migrate toward target cells - one toward egg cell, other toward central cell. Stage 3: Simultaneous fusion events occur - one sperm fuses with egg cell to form diploid zygote, while other sperm fuses with central cell (containing fused polar nuclei) to form triploid primary endosperm cell. This double fertilization is unique to angiosperms.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.18": (
    caption: [Morphological adaptations in flowers that promote outcrossing and prevent self-pollination. Protogynous flowers have stigmas that mature and become receptive before stamens release pollen, ensuring cross-pollination. Protandrous flowers show the reverse temporal pattern - stamens mature before stigmas. Spatial separation through heterostyly also prevents self-pollination: flowers may have either long styles with short stamens or short styles with long stamens, promoting pollen transfer between morphs. Differential timing and spatial arrangements reduce self-pollination and increase genetic diversity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.19": (
    caption: [Comparison of gametophytic and sporophytic self-incompatibility systems. Gametophytic SI: The S-locus genotype of the pollen itself (not parent plant) determines compatibility. Pollen carrying S-alleles matching either stigma S-allele is rejected. Operates in Solanaceae, Rosaceae, Plantaginaceae. Sporophytic SI: The S-locus genotype of the pollen parent (sporophyte) determines compatibility. Dominance relationships between S-alleles affect pollen recognition. Pollen rejected when parent's dominant S-allele matches stigma. Operates in Brassicaceae. Both systems prevent self-fertilization through genetic mechanisms involving S-locus genes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.20": (
    caption: [Brassicaceae sporophytic self-incompatibility system showing molecular recognition mechanism. The male S-determinant is the small cysteine-rich SCR/SP11 protein in the pollen coat, synthesized in tapetum. The female S-determinant is the S-locus receptor kinase (SRK) in stigma papilla cell plasma membrane. During incompatible pollination, SCR/SP11 binds to SRK with matching S-haplotype, triggering signal transduction cascade. This leads to rejection responses including inhibition of pollen hydration, prevention of pollen tube penetration, and blocked pollen germination.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.21": (
    caption: [RNase degradation model for gametophytic self-incompatibility in Solanaceae and Rosaceae. Pistil produces S-RNases that enter pollen tubes growing through the style. In compatible pollination (different S-alleles), pollen-expressed F-box proteins sequester and degrade S-RNases, allowing pollen tube to grow. In incompatible pollination (matching S-alleles), the pollen's cognate S-RNase is not degraded, accumulates in pollen tube cytoplasm, and degrades pollen tube RNA, arresting tube growth. The S-locus encodes both pistil S-RNases and pollen F-box proteins determining specificity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.22": (
    caption: [Arabidopsis seed structure showing major tissue components. Diagram illustrates the mature embryo with two large fleshy cotyledons, embryonic axis with shoot apical meristem, hypocotyl, and radicle. The endosperm forms a single-cell aleurone layer surrounding the embryo. The seed coat (testa) derives from maternal ovule integuments and includes multiple specialized layers: outer epidermis with mucilage, palisade layer with columnar cells and secondary walls, pigment strand, inner integuments, and endothelium. Seeds store lipids and proteins as major reserves.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.23": (
    caption: [Cereal seed structure illustrated by wheat showing specialized tissue organization. The grain is a caryopsis (fruit with fused seed coat and pericarp). Major components include: large starchy endosperm occupying most volume with aleurone layer at periphery containing proteins and lipids; scutellum (single cotyledon) interfacing with endosperm; embryonic axis with shoot (coleoptile) and root (radicle with coleorhiza); and pericarp-seed coat fused layer. The starchy endosperm provides carbohydrate reserves while aleurone produces hydrolytic enzymes during germination. This structure represents the economically important grain crop architecture.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.24": (
    caption: [Development of the endosperm coenocyte in Arabidopsis showing nuclear division and cellularization. Early stages: triploid primary endosperm nucleus undergoes free nuclear divisions without cytokinesis, creating a multinucleate syncytium. Nuclei migrate throughout the elongating central cell. Cellularization begins at the micropylar region and progresses toward chalazal pole. Cell walls form between nuclei creating cellular endosperm. Most endosperm is eventually reabsorbed by the growing embryo during seed maturation, leaving only a thin aleurone layer at the periphery in mature Arabidopsis seeds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.25": (
    caption: [Cross-wall formation in the peripheral endosperm of Arabidopsis during cellularization. The process begins during the globular embryo stage. Radial microtubule arrays organize the coenocyte into nuclear cytoplasmic domains, defining boundaries between adjacent nuclei. Mini-phragmoplasts form at domain boundaries, similar to but smaller than phragmoplasts in typical cell division. Vesicles derived from Golgi fuse at mini-phragmoplasts to form cross-walls, progressively partitioning the syncytium into individual cells. This specialized cytokinesis mechanism creates the cellular endosperm tissue.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.26": (
    caption: [Development of the endosperm coenocyte of cereals showing distinct spatial patterns. Early development: triploid endosperm nucleus located in basal cytoplasm undergoes free nuclear divisions. Nuclei migrate to the periphery of the large coenocytic cell, concentrating at the cell cortex while large central vacuole expands. Cellularization proceeds from periphery inward: nuclei become organized by radial microtubule arrays, mini-phragmoplasts form, vesicles fuse to create cell walls. Unlike Arabidopsis, cereal endosperm persists as starchy tissue occupying most of mature seed volume, serving as the major carbohydrate reserve.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.27": (
    caption: [Examples of asexual embryogenesis (sporophytic apomixis) bypassing sexual reproduction. Kalanchoe produces small propagules - embryo-like structures that differentiate from leaf margins without fertilization. These propagules eventually detach and establish as independent plants. Somatic embryos can be generated in tissue culture from many species using young tissue or anthers as explants. Explants are subjected to osmotic, hormonal, or temperature shock, then grown in recovery media as callus or suspension cultures. Somatic embryogenesis is widely used in plant biotechnology for clonal propagation and crop improvement.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.28": (
    caption: [Development of the ovule integuments into the seed coat of Arabidopsis following fertilization. Pre-fertilization: ovule has two integument layers. Ten days after fertilization: individual cell layers differentiate into specialized types including endothelium (layer 5), palisade cells with thick secondary walls (layer 2), and outer epidermis (layer 1). Mucilage accumulates in apoplast. Fifteen days (seed maturity): cells of all five layers undergo programmed cell death and are crushed together except for epidermis and palisade layer. The mature seed coat provides mechanical protection, regulates water uptake during imbibition, and contains mucilage for seed dispersal and establishment.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.29": (
    caption: [Metabolic and physiological changes during seed maturation in Medicago truncatula showing four phases: embryogenesis, seed filling, late maturation, and pod abscission. Time course shows progressive development over weeks. Water content declines while dry weight increases during seed filling. Seeds acquire desiccation tolerance (measured by germination after rapid drying) and longevity (viability under storage) during late maturation. Germination speed initially increases then dormancy is imposed, shown by increasing time required for 50% germination. These coordinated changes prepare seeds for dispersal, storage, and successful germination.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.30": (
    caption: [Three types of fruit and their flowers: pea, raspberry, and pear, illustrating fruit diversity. Pea (Pisum sativum) produces a simple dry dehiscent fruit (legume pod) from a single carpel containing multiple seeds. Raspberry (Rubus) forms an aggregate fruit composed of many small drupelets, each an individual fruit from separate carpels of a single flower. Pear (Pyrus) develops a pome - an accessory fruit where the fleshy tissue derives from the floral hypanthium surrounding the ovary, with the core representing the true fruit from carpels. These examples demonstrate how fruits develop from different floral parts.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.31": (
    caption: [Nitsch's 1950 experiment on strawberry fruit development demonstrating auxin's role. Strawberry is an aggregate accessory fruit where achenes (true fruits containing seeds) sit on enlarged fleshy receptacle. Removing all achenes prevents receptacle enlargement. A single remaining achene induces localized receptacle growth producing miniature fruit. Exogenous auxin application rescues fruit development even without achenes, producing normal-sized seedless receptacle. Selective removal leaving two achenes creates two separate miniature fruits. These experiments proved that auxin from developing seeds controls fruit flesh development.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.32": (
    caption: [Parthenocarpic fruits compared with fertilized fruits showing seedless fruit development. Wild banana (Musa acuminata banksia) produces seeded fruits after fertilization. Domesticated banana cultivars produce parthenocarpic seedless fruits without fertilization through genetic changes. Wild-type tomato 'Monalbo' produces fertilized fruits with seed-filled locules. Parthenocarpic 'Monalbo' containing mutant arf8 transgene develops seedless fruits with enlarged endocarp but no seeds. Parthenocarpic fruit development can be induced by mutations in auxin response factors (ARF7, ARF8) and GIBERELLIN-INSENSITIVE, indicating hormonal control of fruit set independent of fertilization. This trait has commercial importance for seedless fruit production.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.33": (
    caption: [The structure and regulation of the dehiscence zone in Arabidopsis dry fruit. False-color scanning electron microscopy shows gynoecium with stigma, style, two valves, replum, and valve margins where dehiscence occurs. Cross-sectional diagram reveals septum containing seeds and two-layer dehiscence zone structure. The separation layer consists of small cells that undergo cell wall breakdown. The endocarp layer (lignified layer b) on inner valve surface provides mechanical tension for pod shatter. Transcription factors and miRNAs regulate dehiscence zone specification and differentiation. SHATTERPROOF, INDEHISCENT, and ALCATRAZ transcription factors promote valve margin identity. FRUITFULL and REPLUMLESS prevent ectopic valve margin formation. This regulated dehiscence enables seed dispersal.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.34": (
    caption: [Examples of tissue differentiation in fleshy fruits showing specialized layer development. Raspberry drupelet cross-section shows lignin-stained thickening endocarp (stone) in red, demonstrating sclerification. Peach fruit diagram illustrates three concentric tissue layers characteristic of drupes: outer exocarp (skin), middle mesocarp (fleshy edible tissue), and inner endocarp (hard stone or pit) surrounding the seed. This tissue differentiation pattern creates the mechanical protection and nutritional rewards that facilitate seed dispersal by animals. The lignified endocarp provides hard protective layer while mesocarp offers nutritional incentive.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.35": (
    caption: [Tomato fruit growth showing developmental stages and cellular changes. Photographs display miniature tomato progression from small green fruit through enlargement to red ripe stage. Light microscopy of pericarp cross-sections at 2, 4, 8, and 24 days after anthesis reveals two growth phases: initial cell division period increasing cell number, followed by massive cell expansion phase dramatically increasing cell size. The transition from cell division to cell expansion determines final fruit size. These coordinated cellular processes are hormonally regulated primarily by auxin and gibberellins during early development.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.36": (
    caption: [Phytoene synthase plays a role in lycopene production in tomato pericarp demonstrating carotenoid biosynthesis. Wild-type tomato fruit (left) accumulates high levels of red lycopene pigment at the ripe stage. Tomato with reduced phytoene synthase gene expression (right) fails to accumulate lycopene, remaining yellow-orange. Phytoene synthase catalyzes the first committed step of carotenoid biosynthesis, condensing two geranylgeranyl diphosphate molecules to form phytoene. This colorless precursor undergoes desaturation reactions to produce lycopene. The experiment demonstrates that phytoene synthase is rate-limiting for lycopene accumulation during tomato ripening.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.37": (
    caption: [Examples of pigment formation during fruit ripening showing anthocyanin diversity. Blueberries accumulate more than a dozen different anthocyanins during ripening including malvidin-, delphinidin-, petunidin-, cyanidin-, and peonidin-glycosides, giving deep purple color. Strawberries accumulate pelargonidin-based anthocyanins contributing to red color. Anthocyanins are synthesized through the phenylpropanoid pathway, modified by glycosyltransferases and acyltransferases. These flavonoid pigments serve multiple functions: attracting seed dispersers, providing antioxidant protection, and offering nutritional benefits. Different anthocyanin compositions create species-specific color patterns important for animal-mediated seed dispersal.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.38": (
    caption: [Antisense silencing of ACC synthase and ACC oxidase inhibits ripening and senescence in tomato. Fruits expressing antisense ACS2 (ACC SYNTHASE2) gene fail to ripen in air but remain viable for 70 days, senescing (yellowing) without ripening. Exogenous ethylene application restores ripening. Fruits expressing antisense ACO1 (ACC OXIDASE1) show approximately 95% reduction in ethylene synthesis, still ripen but with greatly reduced overripening and deterioration. Leaf senescence is also delayed in transgenic plants. These experiments demonstrate ethylene's critical role in climacteric fruit ripening and that partial ethylene reduction can extend shelf life while maintaining ripening capacity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.39": (
    caption: [Growth and development of tomato fruits in relation to ethylene effects and ripening physiology. Graph shows fruit growth, respiration rate, and ethylene production over time. Climacteric fruits exhibit characteristic respiratory climacteric - sharp increase in respiration rate coinciding with ethylene production burst at ripening onset. Cell division phase (early development) is followed by cell expansion phase. The climacteric marks transition from mature green to ripening stages. Two ethylene production systems operate: System 1 in immature fruit (low basal ethylene, autoinhibitory) and System 2 at ripening onset (high autocatalytic ethylene production). This ethylene burst triggers coordinated ripening responses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.40": (
    caption: [Tomato mutants ripening inhibitor (rin) and Colorless non-ripening (Cnr) fail to undergo normal ripening. Both mutants remain firm, green, and fail to develop red color, soften, or produce ripening-associated volatiles even when mature. The rin mutant carries deletion affecting the MADS-box transcription factor gene RIPENING INHIBITOR. The Cnr mutant has DNA hypermethylation silencing the COLORLESS NON-RIPENING gene encoding a SQUAMOSA PROMOTER BINDING PROTEIN-box transcription factor. These master regulators control ripening by activating downstream effector genes. The mutations demonstrate that ripening requires coordinated transcriptional regulation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.41": (
    caption: [Major known regulators of ripening in tomato showing transcriptional network hierarchy. Blue rectangles represent transcription factors including master regulators RIN (RIPENING INHIBITOR, MADS-box), CNR (COLORLESS NON-RIPENING, SBP-box), NOR (NON-RIPENING, NAC), and FUL (FRUITFULL, MADS-box). Red labels indicate genes with orthologs in dry dehiscent fruits, suggesting conserved developmental programs. Downstream white boxes show effector genes for ethylene biosynthesis (ACS, ACO), cell wall modification (PG, EXP), and pigment synthesis (PSY). Solid lines indicate activation, dashed lines possible activation. RIN activates multiple pathways. AP2 represses CNR. This network coordinates the ripening syndrome.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "21.42": (
    caption: [Anthocyanin production can be induced in tomato by overexpressing transcription factors from snapdragon (Antirrhinum). Tomatoes normally do not accumulate anthocyanins in fruit tissue. Transgenic tomatoes expressing snapdragon transcription factors DELILA and ROSEA1 that regulate anthocyanin biosynthesis produce purple fruits accumulating high anthocyanin levels. This demonstrates that the enzymatic machinery for anthocyanin synthesis exists in tomato but lacks transcriptional activation. Metabolic engineering by introducing heterologous transcription factors can induce novel pigment accumulation, potentially enhancing nutritional value. This approach has commercial applications for producing fruits with elevated antioxidant content.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
